---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section id="why" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      The question
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      Why would you need one?
    </h2>

    <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      <p>
        The clearest way to answer that is a story most developers have already
        lived, told through React. You started with the core: React rendered
        components and turned events into more components, and that was it. To
        build a real application you stitched the rest on yourself. You picked a
        router. You picked a data-fetching layer. You added a UI component
        library, then a design system on top of it. It worked. But it was a lot
        of work, and <mark>none of it transferred</mark>. Switch teams, switch
        companies, and you rebuilt the same setup from scratch, differently
        every time.
      </p>
      <p>
        Meta-frameworks solved this. Next.js, and later TanStack Start, took all
        that plumbing and put it in a batteries-included box you could move with.
        You still wrote React, but routing, rendering, and data access arrived
        already arranged, so setting up a serious app stopped being someone's
        personal side quest.
      </p>
      <p>
        Harnesses today are the React core. They are excellent at the one
        universal thing they do, and everyone is stitching the rest on by hand:
        custom CLIs, code mode, skills, glue scripts to make an agent reach
        beyond the folder in front of it. It works, and it does not transfer.
      </p>
      <p class="font-medium text-neutral-100">
        A meta-harness is the Next.js of harnesses. The box that arranges the
        pieces, so you can stop building the setup and start doing the work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-5xl">
    <VizPlaceholder
      label="React core with hand-stitched router, data, UI, design system, resolving into a single batteries-included box, then the same shape redrawn for harnesses"
    />
  </div>
</section>
